&gt;&gt;Andrea: And has anybody here seen Whale
Wars, the TV show? OK. Great, we have a few

00:01:23.580 --> 00:01:28.180
Whale Wars fans, but for any of you who haven't
heard of Whale Wars or seen it, it's our hit

00:01:28.180 --> 00:01:35.490
TV show on Animal Planet. It's a reality show
that takes you with us to the front lines

00:01:35.490 --> 00:01:41.750
of our battle to save whales in the Antarctic
Whale Sanctuary from a criminal whaling operation.

00:01:41.750 --> 00:01:48.350
But what we wanted to talk to you today about
is not just what you're gonna see on the TV

00:01:48.350 --> 00:01:53.610
show, but it's really about individual actions
and how it's up to every single one of us

00:01:53.610 --> 00:01:59.200
to really do our part to help save the oceans.
And what we've seen, being out at sea, about

00:01:59.200 --> 00:02:09.180
the impacts of consumers like us, on the oceans.
And so, Tod and I, we personally came up with

00:02:09.180 --> 00:02:11.870
three easy things that people can do in less
than five minutes a day to help save the oceans.

00:02:11.870 --> 00:02:14.959
And those things are to grab a bag, which
is to use reusable shopping bags, water bottles;

00:02:14.959 --> 00:02:18.709
that kind of thing and we actually already
saw that Google has taken a step with that

00:02:18.709 --> 00:02:24.170
and doesn't have bottled water available for
employees. So, I definitely commend Google

00:02:24.170 --> 00:02:28.019
on that. And the second thing that we came
up with is to forgo the fish, which is to

00:02:28.019 --> 00:02:34.280
stop eating fish and other marine life. And
the third thing that we came up with is for

00:02:34.280 --> 00:02:49.819
people to do number one and two, so that's
to grab a bag and to forgo the fish and talk

00:02:49.819 --> 00:02:53.079
about these issues in conservation.

00:02:53.079 --> 00:03:07.420
&gt;&gt;Tod: Yeah. We actually didn't come up with
