[laughter]

00:05:35.720 --> 00:05:43.940
But yeah, they, we also wanna talk about why
we feel so strongly about those three things

00:05:43.940 --> 00:05:53.160
that we mentioned. And what we saw out there
made us believe it so much. And why we're

00:05:53.160 --> 00:06:03.110
willing to risk our lives and join Sea Shepherd
in going down there, and get into these battles

00:06:03.110 --> 00:06:09.000
and all these things that you see on Whale
Wars. I mean--after all--we're not thrill

00:06:09.000 --> 00:06:16.190
seekers, we're not weekend warrior stunt men.
I was a computer geek. I started off working

00:06:16.190 --> 00:06:20.690
at Yahoo. I just left, I'm not evil, either,
so--

00:06:20.690 --> 00:06:21.690
[Andrea laughs]

00:06:21.690 --> 00:06:27.460
and Andrea's a lawyer. We're not paintball
fanatics or anything like that. So, what was

00:06:27.460 --> 00:06:38.490
it that made us drop our nice jobs and our
cushy New York lifestyles and go and put ourselves

00:06:38.490 --> 00:06:43.910
in danger? And the answer is, pretty much,
that the oceans are that important. The oceans

00:06:43.910 --> 00:06:51.390
are so important--especially now--with all
these disasters happening, like the Gulf and

00:06:51.390 --> 00:07:01.400
with global warming and everything. Because
how we come out as a race, at the end of all

00:07:01.400 --> 00:07:11.140
these things, is really gonna be determined
by how healthy our oceans are and how much

00:07:11.140 --> 00:07:24.400
life there is in the oceans to replace what
was lost. How much in the oceans can balance

00:07:24.400 --> 00:07:35.320
and bring balance and regulate to all the
ecosystems that come out of this OK. And so

00:07:35.320 --> 00:07:39.170
that's why we decided that--

00:07:39.170 --> 00:07:41.480
[cell phone rings]

00:07:41.480 --> 00:07:51.550
it's important enough to risk our lives for
joining Sea Shepherd. And we've picked Sea

00:07:51.550 --> 00:07:59.250
Shepherd, in particular, because it's so effective.
Sea Shepherd is a very effective group. We're

00:07:59.250 --> 00:08:06.340
not a group of protesters. We don't wave signs
and banners and ask poachers to stop killing

00:08:06.340 --> 00:08:13.580
whales. When we say we're gonna save whales,
we actually go and save whales. A lot of people

00:08:13.580 --> 00:08:23.540
know of our Antarctic campaign. That's our
most famous one. But we also do a whole lot

00:08:23.540 --> 00:08:30.920
of other campaigns around the world. Right
now, Sea Shepherd's main ship, the Steve Irwin--or

00:08:30.920 --> 00:08:41.960
one of our two ships--the Steve Irwin is in
the Mediterranean right now saving the last

00:08:41.960 --> 00:08:53.639
of the blue fin tuna on earth. Some of the
last ones from illegal poaching. We also do

00:08:53.639 --> 00:09:04.149
anti-long-lining campaigns and we also do
anti bottom trawling campaigns. Bottom trawling

00:09:04.149 --> 00:09:14.070
is probably the worst ecological disaster
that we cause on purpose. And we save baby

00:09:14.070 --> 00:09:26.180
seals in Canada from the seal clubbing and
we have a field office in Galapagos. That's

00:09:26.180 --> 00:09:33.360
very effective, actually, because that field
office works directly with the Ecuadorian

00:09:33.360 --> 00:09:41.440
government in protecting the marine reserve
there. So, the more we found out, the more

00:09:41.440 --> 00:09:56.589
willing I was to give up this lifestyle and
just go out there and save as much as I could.

00:09:56.589 --> 00:10:03.130
When Sea Shepherd called and said, "Hey, do
wanna come down to the Antarctic? Can you

00:10:03.130 --> 00:10:09.329
actually buy a ticket tonight to come to Australia
to meet our ship?" I jumped to the chance.

00:10:09.329 --> 00:10:16.399
I bought a ticket, I quit my job that day,
I flew down to Australia in a couple days.

00:10:16.399 --> 00:10:26.120
I got off the plane and realized I didn't
know where to go. I asked people, "Where do

00:10:26.120 --> 00:10:29.970
you keep your ships in this town?"

00:10:29.970 --> 00:10:30.970
[laughter]

00:10:30.970 --> 00:10:41.050
I went down there. I was an American tourist
looking for Steve Irwin, that came off as

00:10:41.050 --> 00:10:43.420
well as it sounds.

00:10:43.420 --> 00:10:44.420
[laughter]

00:10:44.420 --> 00:10:53.680
But then, like within less than a week with
this group we went down there and we saved

00:10:53.680 --> 00:11:02.730
500 whales from getting harpooned. And so,
it's just direct action like that that makes

00:11:02.730 --> 00:11:11.050
us really want to just keep on working with
Sea Shepherd all the time.

00:11:11.050 --> 00:11:14.650
&gt;&gt;Andrea: Mm-hmm. And.

00:11:14.650 --> 00:11:17.220
&gt;&gt;Lee: So, go ahead.

00:11:17.220 --> 00:11:25.230
&gt;&gt;Andrea: OK. And when I first stumbled on
Sea Shepherd, I had found out about Sea Shepherd's

00:11:25.230 --> 00:11:35.470
just absolute commitment to saving lives.
And as a public defender I'd always been very

00:11:35.470 --> 00:11:40.629
passionate and committed to saving lives.
And I've just been doing that in the courtroom.

00:11:40.629 --> 00:11:45.410
But with Sea Shepherd, I transferred that
passion and commitment to saving lives to

00:11:45.410 --> 00:11:54.869
saving our oceans and life in the oceans.
And I remember, I first joined the Bob Barker,

00:11:54.869 --> 00:12:05.040
which is our newest ship and yes, it was actually
bought for by Mr. Bob Barker, the game show

00:12:05.040 --> 00:12:20.120
host. He made a generous donation to Sea Shepherd
of five million dollars to buy the ship last

00:12:20.120 --> 00:12:21.270
fall. And--

00:12:21.270 --> 00:12:23.519
&gt;&gt;Lee: Five hundred million?

00:12:23.519 --> 00:12:26.350
&gt;&gt;Andrea: Five million. Five million.

00:12:26.350 --> 00:12:33.490
&gt;&gt;Lee: Five million. I was like, "God, that's
like [ ]." The Price is Right has been good

00:12:33.490 --> 00:12:34.490
to him.

00:12:34.490 --> 00:12:35.490
[laughter]

00:12:35.490 --> 00:12:41.100
&gt;&gt;Andrea: No, five million. And, and we had
just bought the ship and in Ghana and actually,

00:12:41.100 --> 00:12:48.360
interestingly enough, it was a former Norwegian
whaling vessel. But now we're using that same

00:12:48.360 --> 00:12:53.120
Norwegian whaling vessel to actually go down
and save whales. So, but I remember the first

00:12:53.120 --> 00:13:05.940
day that we were on the ship and there were
migrating whales that came alongside the ship.

00:13:05.940 --> 00:13:13.009
And these migrating whales were actually down
on their way to the whale sanctuary in Antarctica.

00:13:13.009 --> 00:13:23.480
And, at the time, all I could think about
was, "Oh my gosh, these are the same whales

00:13:23.480 --> 00:13:30.379
that are headed a few thousand miles down
to the Southern Ocean and we have to be there.

00:13:30.379 --> 00:13:37.690
We have to get the ship ready to be able to
save them because we're gonna be their only

00:13:37.690 --> 00:13:43.550
defense, once they're down in the Southern
ocean, from the criminal whaling operation."

00:13:43.550 --> 00:13:51.870
But that was my thought was just a few months
down the line, we're gonna have to save these

00:13:51.870 --> 00:14:00.350
whales. Well, later that day, I started really
noticing that all around us in the ocean--and

00:14:00.350 --> 00:14:06.740
where these whales were migrating--there was
actually plastic bags floating everywhere.

00:14:06.740 --> 00:14:18.040
And whales, turtles, birds and other animals,
they actually eat plastic thinking that it

00:14:18.040 --> 00:14:22.160
was food. Because millions of years of evolution,
unfortunately, hasn't prepared them for the

00:14:22.160 --> 00:14:26.480
reality that now that there's plastic all
in the oceans, we actually very much have

00:14:26.480 --> 00:14:32.519
a plastic sea. And all this plastic, it was
coming down out of rivers off the mainland.

00:14:32.519 --> 00:14:37.540
And it's the very same thing that's going
on here in New York. In Manhattan, we're on

00:14:37.540 --> 00:14:43.370
an island. And during a windy day or storm,
all the trash, all the loose plastic bags,

00:14:43.370 --> 00:14:49.290
all the cigarette butts, everything else,
it just blows right into the Hudson River,

00:14:49.290 --> 00:14:58.410
into the East River. And actually ends up
in the same place in the oceans that the trash

00:14:58.410 --> 00:15:05.519
off Western Africa does. And the trash all
congregates in these huge, floating, plastic,

00:15:05.519 --> 00:15:11.769
swirling gyres in the ocean. And researchers
have actually found that the, the density

00:15:11.769 --> 00:15:18.369
of plastic to plankton is six to one in these
areas. So, it was just--it's just flabbergasting.

00:15:18.369 --> 00:15:25.800
It's the same thing as if you were eating
your morning cereal and there's six time as

00:15:25.800 --> 00:15:39.899
much plastic in your cereal as actual cereal,
but you can't tell the difference what's what.

00:15:39.899 --> 00:15:47.649
And so that's what's going on in, in the oceans
right now. And it's just because people let

00:15:47.649 --> 00:15:54.889
their trash go into the rivers, which goes
right into the oceans. And so that's actually

00:15:54.889 --> 00:15:59.910
how we came up with the first thing that we
think people can do to help save the oceans

00:15:59.910 --> 00:16:08.300
and just less than five minutes a day and
that's to take a reusable shopping bag with

00:16:08.300 --> 00:16:19.589
you when you, when you go out for the day.
There's little ones that fit in your pocket,

00:16:19.589 --> 00:16:28.980
fit over your shoulder, take it with you.
They're small, they're sturdy and uses even

00:16:28.980 --> 00:16:37.730
less plastic and petroleum to produce those.
And same with the water bottles, which I know,

00:16:37.730 --> 00:16:51.110
I know Google's already working on, so that's
great. And that was just what I saw, though,

00:16:51.110 --> 00:16:53.730
in the first day of--

00:16:53.730 --> 00:16:54.779
[man coughs]

00:16:54.779 --> 00:17:02.740
being on a ship. And that night, though, was
a whole nother story. And it presented a whole

00:17:02.740 --> 00:17:08.919
nother danger to the whales. Because what
happened that first night was that there were

00:17:08.919 --> 00:17:15.939
all these fishing ships that came out. And
there was fishing nets everywhere and fishing

00:17:15.939 --> 00:17:23.550
ships. And even with our radar and binoculars,
we actually had trouble navigating through

00:17:23.550 --> 00:17:31.280
all these fishing nets. And, and I thought,
"Oh my gosh, how are the whales gonna navigate

00:17:31.280 --> 00:17:37.779
through these?" And, unfortunately, whales
don't always make it through. And I suspect

00:17:37.779 --> 00:17:45.409
that not all the whales that we saw migrating
probably even made it down to the Southern

00:17:45.409 --> 00:17:51.620
Ocean Whale Sanctuary. Because, unfortunately,
commercial fishing uses massive, massive nets

00:17:51.620 --> 00:18:00.230
and whales, dolphins, sea birds, turtles and
everything else, happens to swim into it just

00:18:00.230 --> 00:18:15.559
to catch a few specific fish. And, while most
people don't eat whale, most people do eat

00:18:15.559 --> 00:18:23.899
fish. And so, part of protecting the whales
and protecting the oceans is, is not eating

00:18:23.899 --> 00:18:43.190
fish. And that's how we came up with the second
thing, which is to forgo the fish. And this

00:18:43.190 --> 00:18:56.529
also hit home a lot more, actually. Jumping
ahead to our very last day of the campaign,

00:18:56.529 --> 00:19:16.070
we were all--at this point--we were all the
way down in Antarctica, by the continent.

00:19:16.070 --> 00:19:29.590
And this is far, far, far as you can get from
humanity. We were down this beautiful, beautiful

00:19:29.590 --> 00:19:39.690
area called Mackenzie Bay, down by the continent.
And this was as area that was so pristine

00:19:39.690 --> 00:19:48.340
and stunning and just was full of whales and
seals and birds and penguins and really just

00:19:48.340 --> 00:20:09.331
a realm that was for them. It was a ice realm,
a watery realm and it was a realm just for

00:20:09.331 --> 00:20:20.940
those animals in that sanctuary. But, as we
were chasing a whaling ship, we happened to

00:20:20.940 --> 00:20:30.550
pass a bright orange buoy and later on we
stopped to investigate. And it turned out

00:20:30.550 --> 00:20:40.200
this buoy was an illegally set fishing net
and it was five miles long. So, it was a fishing

00:20:40.200 --> 00:20:49.549
net that actually would have stretched from
Battery Park all the way up to Central Park.

00:20:49.549 --> 00:20:57.620
And it was gonna catch every single thing
that swam into it. And so, as Sea Shepherd

00:20:57.620 --> 00:21:07.269
and as law enforcement organization and as
a marine conservation organization, we confiscated

00:21:07.269 --> 00:21:16.090
that net. And as we were leaving Mackenzie
Bay, we actually caught that ship and it had

00:21:16.090 --> 00:21:34.380
set another net. So, it was ten miles of fishing
line all the down in Antarctica. And what's

00:21:34.380 --> 00:21:44.159
significant about that is not just that there's
illegal fishing all the way at the end of

00:21:44.159 --> 00:21:59.570
the planet. But that there's fishing at all,
all the way at the end of the planet. And

00:21:59.570 --> 00:22:14.010
the reason that there's fishing all the way
by Antarctica is because all the big fish

00:22:14.010 --> 00:22:27.440
are gone in the oceans. And since 1950, industrial
fishing has taken out 90 percent of all big

00:22:27.440 --> 00:22:32.669
fish in the oceans. I mean, think, this planet
is four billion years old, 60 years isn't

00:22:32.669 --> 00:22:39.159
even hardly a blink in our lifetime, in this
planets lifetime. And so, that means that

00:22:39.159 --> 00:22:53.289
we're actually in the middle of a mass extinction
and it's a mass extinction in our oceans.

00:22:53.289 --> 00:23:03.750
And our oceans cover 70 percent of this planet.
We're a blue planet. So it's a huge, huge

00:23:03.750 --> 00:23:09.450
emergency what's going on in our oceans. And
that's, that's why we're willing to risk our

00:23:09.450 --> 00:23:19.990
lives to save the last ten percent of the
fish and the shadow populations of whales

00:23:19.990 --> 00:23:35.190
that still are in our oceans. And we personally
think that what we should be doing is not

00:23:35.190 --> 00:23:43.210
talking about how we can just keep continue
eating the last ten percent of the fish that

00:23:43.210 --> 00:23:49.409
are in the oceans, but how we can have we
can have that natural abundance of fish and

00:23:49.409 --> 00:23:50.409
biodiversity and life on this planet and how
we can go back to having a perfect ocean.

