economically. And same with the fishing fleets.
They operate on a very small margin a lot

00:25:23.019 --> 00:25:30.190
of times of profit. Say, for example, bottom
trawling. The only reason--what bottom trawling

00:25:30.190 --> 00:25:35.929
is--is basically bulldozing the ocean floor
and coral, there's deep sea coral, just bulldozing

00:25:35.929 --> 00:25:43.330
it to catch a few fish. So, it's the same
thing as, just bulldozing the rain forest

00:25:43.330 --> 00:25:53.480
to catch a few birds. So what we--what Sea
Shepherd has done is they--we did a deep sea

00:25:53.480 --> 00:26:00.820
bottom trawling campaign to stop areas of
illegal bottom trawling. And since bottom

00:26:00.820 --> 00:26:09.750
trawlers, there's only about two hundred ships
worldwide that are causing all this destruction

00:26:09.750 --> 00:26:12.940
and they operate on fishing subsidies. And
actually it wouldn't be possible or profitable

00:26:12.940 --> 00:26:17.200
for them to continue some of those fishing
without some of the fishing subsidies, but

00:26:17.200 --> 00:26:19.350
it all revolves around economics.

00:26:19.350 --> 00:26:22.620
&gt;&gt;Lee: I see. So, do you have any examples?

00:26:22.620 --> 00:26:28.889
&gt;&gt;Tod: Well, in the Galapagos, we always also
have a pretty fun exercise where we have a

00:26:28.889 --> 00:26:36.230
lot of poaching equipment and poaching operations
in the marine reserve. And actually, each

00:26:36.230 --> 00:26:48.019
week, we're seeing them coming from countries
further and further away cause there's just

00:26:48.019 --> 00:27:03.509
no fish in between the Galapagos and, and
even Asia, China now. And so we find a lot

00:27:03.509 --> 00:27:13.500
of this equipment in the park. So what we
do is that we take it because--it's more--it

00:27:13.500 --> 00:27:30.139
cost more than our stuff, so we might as well
use it. And then we take it apart and we re-purpose

00:27:30.139 --> 00:27:40.720
them into things that we can try to use to
save the environment, like our office in Galapagos,

00:27:40.720 --> 00:27:47.350
now partially powered by solar panels that
we've taken from marine buoys that are used

00:27:47.350 --> 00:27:52.250
as fish aggregate devices. And we use antennas--

00:27:52.250 --> 00:27:54.259
&gt;&gt;Andrea: Mm-hmm.

00:27:54.259 --> 00:28:04.679
&gt;&gt;Tod: that we take from a lot of these fish
devices, use them in our communications gear.

00:28:04.679 --> 00:28:11.770
And so I like the, I like this project because
I like irony. And so--

00:28:11.770 --> 00:28:17.270
&gt;&gt;Lee: Effectively, you're having like the
