00:40:52.180 --> 00:40:53.940
&gt;&gt;Andrea: Sure.

00:40:53.940 --> 00:40:58.150
&gt;&gt;Lee: so, where, how does that line, where
is that line sitting and, and how does it

00:40:58.150 --> 00:40:59.870
move? Or does it?

00:40:59.870 --> 00:41:03.130
&gt;&gt;Tod: Battles look chaotic and stuff when
you see them on the show, etc. Especially

00:41:03.130 --> 00:41:06.540
when everyone is shooting at each other and
stuff, but it's actually very, very well planned.

00:41:06.540 --> 00:41:07.550
Everything is meticulously planned and well
placed. For instance, when we attacked the

00:41:07.550 --> 00:41:08.550
Nishu Maru with, with our stink bombs and
so forth--

00:41:08.550 --> 00:41:09.550
&gt;&gt;Lee: Mm-hmm.

00:41:09.550 --> 00:41:10.990
&gt;&gt;Tod: We're aiming only for whaling decks
that no people are on because the number one

00:41:10.990 --> 00:41:17.660
rule is that you can't harm any people. And
so what the stink bombs do is that we're actually

00:41:17.660 --> 00:41:20.210
aiming for whaling decks and when the stink
bombs hit the whaling decks, it spoils any

00:41:20.210 --> 00:41:21.210
meats that you might put on there so they
can't process whales on there.

00:41:21.210 --> 00:41:22.210
&gt;&gt;Lee: Right. Gotcha.

00:41:22.210 --> 00:41:23.210
&gt;&gt;Tod: It also smells so bad, that after an
attack, we literally have to close all our

00:41:23.210 --> 00:41:24.210
portholes and windows--

00:41:24.210 --> 00:41:25.210
[Andrea laughs]

00:41:25.210 --> 00:41:26.210
for like a whole week. When we're anywhere
within a half mile of that, cause that how

00:41:26.210 --> 00:41:28.390
bad it stinks. And in fact, we don't see anyone
on their decks for maybe a week after an attack.

00:41:28.390 --> 00:41:29.390
[laughter]

00:41:29.390 --> 00:41:30.390
And the other thing that we throw is called
methylcellulose, which we throw on top of

00:41:30.390 --> 00:41:31.390
the stink bombs. And methylcellulose is the
chemical substance coats pills--

00:41:31.390 --> 00:41:32.390
&gt;&gt;Lee: Mm-hmm.

00:41:32.390 --> 00:41:33.390
&gt;&gt;Tod: that makes them easier to swallow.
So, when you see people throwing stink bombs

00:41:33.390 --> 00:41:34.390
on your decks and stuff, you're first instinct
is to use a hose and wash it off. But when

00:41:34.390 --> 00:41:35.390
you wash off the methylcellulose, moisture
activates it and makes it super slippery so

00:41:35.390 --> 00:41:36.390
you can't wash anything off of it. So, it
looks really chaotic, but it's, it's really

00:41:36.390 --> 00:41:37.640
very well planned. One of the only spontaneous
things that we threw was this, there was this

00:41:37.640 --> 00:41:39.250
horrible vegan salad dressing that we no one
like on the ship.

00:41:39.250 --> 00:41:40.250
[Andrea laughs]

00:41:40.250 --> 00:41:46.920
And, and we're starting to run out of things
to throw and we're like, "What do we throw

00:41:46.920 --> 00:41:47.920
out?" And we're like, "Let's get rid of the
salad dressing."

00:41:47.920 --> 00:41:48.920
[Andrea laughs]

00:41:48.920 --> 00:41:49.920
And so we chucked the salad dressing, we just
thought, "Oh,that's the end of that, this

00:41:49.920 --> 00:41:50.920
horrible imitation blue cheese stuff."

00:41:50.920 --> 00:41:52.950
[Andrea laughs]

00:41:52.950 --> 00:41:54.000
And we thought that was the end of that, and
then two days later, the front line, the front

00:41:54.000 --> 00:41:55.000
headlines out of Japan were, "Terrorist group
throws white chemical substance."

00:41:55.000 --> 00:41:56.000
[Andrea laughs]

00:41:56.000 --> 00:41:57.000
And what is it? Is it anthrax?

00:41:57.000 --> 00:41:58.000
[laughter]

00:41:58.000 --> 00:41:59.000
What could they have? They had people with
hazmat suits out there. They're like --so

00:41:59.000 --> 00:42:00.000
they never released their research findings
on it.

00:42:00.000 --> 00:42:01.000
[laughter]

00:42:01.000 --> 00:42:02.000
&gt;&gt;Lee: I imagine not. No, blue cheese, ill
prepared. Let's see, what else. So, I know

00:42:02.000 --> 00:42:03.000
on the side of the ship it'll say, "We've
sunk X amount of vessels," or whatever--

00:42:03.000 --> 00:42:04.000
&gt;&gt;Tod: Mm-hmm.

00:42:04.000 --> 00:42:05.000
&gt;&gt;Lee: I mean, is it, we've never seen that
happen on the show. Is it something--do you

00:42:05.000 --> 00:42:06.000
do it at sea? And I know people will be like,
"Well, that's not right. You shouldn't go

00:42:06.000 --> 00:42:07.000
and sink vessels because people could die
and that kind of thing." So, tell me more

00:42:07.000 --> 00:42:08.000
about how, how you guys sink vessels.

00:42:08.000 --> 00:42:09.000
&gt;&gt;Andrea: Well, Sea Shepherd has a long history
of protecting whales and it actually started

00:42:09.000 --> 00:42:10.000
back in the late 70s. And Paul Watson, whose
our founder, he went after a pirate whaling

00:42:10.000 --> 00:42:11.000
ship named the Sierra. And the Sierra was
a pirate whaling ship and it wasn't registered

00:42:11.000 --> 00:42:12.000
to anyone and it just went around the world
